<h1>@HI{{te}}-form cause</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @FORMATION{{@Vte{{}}, ...}}
<li> @FORMATION{{@Vnaistem{{}}@HI{{nakute}}, ...}}
<li> @FORMATION{{@Aistem{{}}@HI{{kute}}, ...}}
<li> @FORMATION{{@Anastem{{}}@HI{{de}}, ...}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
The subordinate clause presents a cause and the main clause states the consequence produced by that cause. Note that
this pattern, unlike @HI{{kara}} has many restrictions on its usage.
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
The contents of the main clause must not contain volition.
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
The main clause often contains verbs and adjectives that express feelings.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{house^tribe}}ni@EM{{@KJ{{meeting}}enakute}},@KJ{{loneliness}}shiidesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I miss my family.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
The main clause often contains potential verbs to and verbs to express state.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{tale}}ga@EM{{@KJ{{duplicate^miscellaneous}}de}},yokuwakarimasendeshita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The story was complicated so I could not understand it well.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
The main clause often contains a situation in the past.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{matter^happenstance}}ga@EM{{atte}},@KT{{basu}}ga@KJ{{slow}}reteshimaimashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The bus was delayed by an accident.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
The subordinate clause must occur chronologically before the main clause. So it is not allowed, for example,
for the subordinate clause to represent a future event and the main clause to represent an event in the present.
</p>

